summary_markdown: This table presents a comparative analysis of leading brands across various product categories in 1923 versus 1997. The structure highlights shifts in market dominance over a 74-year period, showcasing both continuity and significant change. For instance, while Wrigley maintained leadership in chewing gum and Gillette in razors, many other categories saw a complete turnover of top brands. Categories like cleansers, five-cent mint candies, peanut butter, soft drinks, coffee, laundry soap, cigarettes, shoes, and candy all display entirely new sets of leading companies in 1997 compared to 1923. This demonstrates a dynamic evolution of consumer markets, with established brands being replaced by new entrants or evolving product lines.
